Ahem, you know what?

760
00:41:49,969 --> 00:41:52,471
Omelet, you're all right with me.

761
00:41:52,888 --> 00:41:54,098
- Ahmet.
- Ahmet.

762
00:41:54,181 --> 00:41:55,349
What kind of name is that?

763
00:41:55,391 --> 00:41:56,642
I'm Turkish.

764
00:41:56,725 --> 00:41:57,935
Well, you know what?

765
00:41:58,018 --> 00:42:00,896
I guess Jack Lauderdale's bad 
luck is my good fortune.

766
00:42:01,063 --> 00:42:04,108
I knew that Atlantic Records
was bigger than Swing Time.

767
00:42:04,191 --> 00:42:06,735
You guys do good music.
I dig Atlantic.

768
00:42:06,819 --> 00:42:08,279
You could have fooled me.

769
00:42:08,362 --> 00:42:11,031
Well, you know, I gotta keep 
my eye on you city boys.

770
00:42:11,615 --> 00:42:13,451
Down home,
we call it "country dumb."

771
00:42:15,578 --> 00:42:17,413
Hey, man, it ain't Turkish.

772
00:42:22,460 --> 00:42:24,753
♪ Went to see my sweetheart ♪

773
00:42:25,671 --> 00:42:28,424
♪ Last night around about ten ♪

774
00:42:29,008 --> 00:42:32,386
♪ She said, move, sweet papa ♪

775
00:42:33,220 --> 00:42:35,723
♪ Squeeze me every now and then ♪

776
00:42:35,973 --> 00:42:37,725
What do you think?

777
00:42:37,766 --> 00:42:40,186
Man, nobody wants
another Nat King Cole.

778
00:42:41,353 --> 00:42:43,314
♪ 'Cause she sleep that way ♪

779
00:42:43,397 --> 00:42:46,400
♪ The midnight hour ♪

780
00:42:47,651 --> 00:42:50,237
♪ Has found me lonely ♪

781
00:42:51,489 --> 00:42:53,407
♪ So unhappy ♪

782
00:42:54,700 --> 00:42:56,452
♪ As I can be ♪

783
00:42:56,619 --> 00:42:59,497
Ahmet, it's just
like Charles Brown.

784
00:43:01,707 --> 00:43:04,126
Okay, I'll talk to him.

785
00:43:06,754 --> 00:43:09,590
All right, fellas, that's a cut.
That's a cut, fellas.

786
00:43:10,257 --> 00:43:11,509
Fellas!

787
00:43:11,592 --> 00:43:12,927
Band can take five.

788
00:43:13,052 --> 00:43:14,386
He just don't get it.

789
00:43:14,470 --> 00:43:17,431
You either sound original,
or you got nothin'.

790
00:43:17,556 --> 00:43:19,767
Ahmet, what'd you think of that?

791
00:43:19,892 --> 00:43:23,062
Ray, I want to tell you something, 
and I don't want you to take it wrong.

792
00:43:23,145 --> 00:43:24,438
Then give it to me right.

793
00:43:24,522 --> 00:43:27,942
I signed you because I sensed
something special in you ...

794
00:43:27,983 --> 00:43:31,195
not because you sound like
Nat Cole or Charles Brown.

795
00:43:31,278 --> 00:43:33,113
I thought you like what I do.

796
00:43:33,155 --> 00:43:35,116
We ... we love the timbre
of your voice,

797
00:43:35,157 --> 00:43:37,409
we like your virtuosity,
your energy ...

798
00:43:37,493 --> 00:43:38,744
But not my music.

799
00:43:38,828 --> 00:43:40,246
Come on, man, I didn't say that.

800
00:43:40,746 --> 00:43:42,748
Ahmet, this is what I do, man.

801
00:43:42,832 --> 00:43:44,959
I gotta make a living.
This is what the people want.

802
00:43:45,042 --> 00:43:46,627
I don't know no other way.

803
00:43:46,710 --> 00:43:48,462
We got to help you find one.

804
00:43:48,504 --> 00:43:50,840
Look, let's try a little
change of pace, okay?

805
00:43:50,923 --> 00:43:52,299
You're familiar with stride piano?

806
00:43:52,383 --> 00:43:55,678
You kidding me, man? The man who I 
learned the piano from is a stride player.

807
00:43:55,761 --> 00:43:58,764
Okay, I got a song.
It's called "The Mess Around".

808
00:43:58,848 --> 00:44:00,683
"The Mess Around."
Cute title. Who wrote it?

809
00:44:00,766 --> 00:44:02,143
I did.

810
00:44:02,393 --> 00:44:03,811
Ah, you wrote it.

811
00:44:03,894 --> 00:44:04,895
Yeah.

812
00:44:05,312 --> 00:44:06,647
Well, sing it to me, man.

813
00:44:06,939 --> 00:44:08,107
- Sing it?
- Yeah.

814
00:44:08,190 --> 00:44:09,817
It ain't like
I can read the lyrics.

815
00:44:09,900 --> 00:44:12,486
Okay.
Well, it's the key of G.

816
00:44:12,570 --> 00:44:13,988
Okay. Key of G.

817
00:44:15,156 --> 00:44:16,115
Uh-huh.

818
00:44:16,949 --> 00:44:17,950
Yeah.

819
00:44:18,117 --> 00:44:20,953
Yeah, but it's a kind of
Pete Johnson thing.

820
00:44:21,036 --> 00:44:22,413
Pete Johnson.

821
00:44:24,206 --> 00:44:25,875
Yeah, yeah, that's it.

822
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:28,043
You like that?
Here we go. Two, three, four.

823
00:44:28,127 --> 00:44:31,422
♪ You can talk
about the pit barbecue ♪

824
00:44:31,505 --> 00:44:33,716
♪ The band was jumpin',
the people, too ♪

825
00:44:33,799 --> 00:44:35,801
♪ They're doin' the mess around ♪

826
00:44:36,635 --> 00:44:38,637
♪ They're doin' the mess around ♪

827
00:44:39,555 --> 00:44:41,474
♪ They're doin' the mess around ♪

828
00:44:41,557 --> 00:44:43,517
♪ Everybody doin'
the mess around ♪

829
00:44:43,601 --> 00:44:45,769
All right, that's good.
Let me take it from here.

830
00:44:45,853 --> 00:44:49,398
♪ Now this band's gonna
play from nine to one ♪

831
00:44:49,482 --> 00:44:52,067
♪ Everybody here's gonna
have some fun ♪

832
00:44:52,193 --> 00:44:53,944
♪ Doin' the mess around ♪

833
00:44:54,737 --> 00:44:56,947
♪ Ah, doin' the mess around ♪

834
00:44:58,574 --> 00:45:00,743
♪ They doin' the mess around ♪

835
00:45:00,868 --> 00:45:02,953
♪ Everybody doin'
the mess around ♪

836
00:45:05,080 --> 00:45:08,542
♪ Now you see that girl
with that diamond ring ♪

837
00:45:09,168 --> 00:45:11,962
♪ She knows
how to shake that thing ♪

838
00:45:12,421 --> 00:45:13,964
♪ Mess around ♪

839
00:45:14,548 --> 00:45:16,509
♪ I declare she can mess around ♪

840
00:45:18,093 --> 00:45:19,845
♪ Ah, mess around ♪

841
00:45:20,262 --> 00:45:22,598
♪ Everybody do the mess around ♪

842
00:45:28,687 --> 00:45:30,189
Now we got something!

843
00:45:30,272 --> 00:45:31,774
That's all right there.

844
00:45:33,275 --> 00:45:34,568
What do you think, Ahmet?

845
00:45:34,610 --> 00:45:35,653
Great, Ray!

846
00:45:35,736 --> 00:45:36,862
Unbelievable!

847
00:45:36,946 --> 00:45:38,030
Who's that?

848
00:45:39,031 --> 00:45:41,242
Ray, I want you to meet
my new partner, Jerry.

849
00:45:41,325 --> 00:45:42,868
Mr. Ray Charles, Jerry Wexler.

850
00:45:42,952 --> 00:45:43,953
Hey.

851
00:45:44,036 --> 00:45:47,081
Don't worry, Ray. I'm going to 
step back, I'm gonna watch,

852
00:45:47,164 --> 00:45:49,583
I'm gonna learn how to produce 
a record. I'm in awe.

853
00:45:49,625 --> 00:45:50,876
That was out of sight.

854
00:45:50,960 --> 00:45:52,753
That's some running
and riffing, man!

855
00:45:53,045 --> 00:45:54,755
Well, this'll make you shout, man.

856
00:46:02,847 --> 00:46:05,599
We're listening to that
new recording, Mess Around ...

857
00:46:05,683 --> 00:46:07,977
by Atlantic recording artist,
Ray Charles.

858
00:46:08,060 --> 00:46:11,564
And we have the gentleman
live here in the KCOH studios.

859
00:46:11,647 --> 00:46:14,692
So, Ray, when you're not making your 
own music, what do you listen to?

860
00:46:14,775 --> 00:46:18,445
You know what, the fact is, King Bee, 
I really and truly love gospel.

861
00:46:18,487 --> 00:46:21,407
One of my favorite groups
is from right here in Houston:

862
00:46:21,490 --> 00:46:23,325
The Cecil Shaw Singers.

863
00:46:23,534 --> 00:46:27,079
You heard it: Ray Charles endorses
Houston's own Cecil Shaw.

864
00:46:27,163 --> 00:46:29,081
We'll be playing
gospel all day Sunday ...

865
00:46:29,165 --> 00:46:30,833
but right now,
let's hear some more ...

866
00:46:30,916 --> 00:46:32,543
of that Mess Around
by Ray Charles.

867
00:46:32,626 --> 00:46:33,961
K.B., line 1.

868
00:46:36,338 --> 00:46:37,673
King Bee.

869
00:46:39,383 --> 00:46:40,384
Mmm-hmm.

870
00:46:41,385 --> 00:46:43,053
Yeah, he's right here.

871
00:46:43,679 --> 00:46:46,265
Miss Della Antwine
of the Cecil Shaw Singers.

872
00:46:49,727 --> 00:46:51,562
Hello, Miss Antwine.

873
00:46:51,979 --> 00:46:54,732
You sung tenor in
Jesus Is My Shepherd, right?

874
00:46:54,815 --> 00:46:56,025
Yes.

875
00:46:56,859 --> 00:46:58,611
How did you pick me out?

876
00:46:58,694 --> 00:47:01,655
Actually,
I ... I hear like you see.

877
00:47:02,406 --> 00:47:05,451
Like that hummingbird outside 
the window, for instance.

878
00:47:11,665 --> 00:47:12,917
I can't hear her.

879
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:14,251
You have to listen.

880
00:47:32,311 --> 00:47:33,354
Yes.

881
00:47:33,437 --> 00:47:34,438
Yeah.

882
00:47:34,730 --> 00:47:35,856
Yes, you can.

883
00:47:35,940 --> 00:47:36,982
OH-OH.

884
00:47:37,066 --> 00:47:38,025
You hear that?

885
00:47:38,108 --> 00:47:39,151
What?

886
00:47:39,902 --> 00:47:42,029
Her heart just skipped a beat.

887
00:47:44,281 --> 00:47:46,158
Oh, did you like my record?

888
00:47:46,450 --> 00:47:48,828
The one that King Bee was playin'?

889
00:47:50,246 --> 00:47:51,872
It was very nice.

890
00:47:52,123 --> 00:47:54,333
Different than the others.

891
00:47:54,917 --> 00:47:56,836
I've heard a lot of your music.

892
00:47:56,919 --> 00:47:58,462
Was it very nice, too?

893
00:47:58,546 --> 00:48:00,798
Look, Miss Antwine, if you
don't really like the record,

894
00:48:00,881 --> 00:48:04,260
you ain't got to beat around the bush 
with me. I mean, my mama never did.

895
00:48:04,343 --> 00:48:06,637
It's not that I don't
enjoy your music.

896
00:48:06,720 --> 00:48:09,056
It's just that I feel
I've heard it before.

897
00:48:09,098 --> 00:48:11,642
I keep wondering what the 
real Ray Charles sound like.

898
00:48:11,725 --> 00:48:13,185
Ray Charles? Who's he?

899
00:48:13,269 --> 00:48:15,187
Nobody, if you don't know.

900
00:48:15,271 --> 00:48:16,230
Huh?

901
00:48:17,064 --> 00:48:19,525
Sorry. I should have
kept my mouth shut.

902
00:48:19,608 --> 00:48:21,777
Oh, no, no.
Then you wouldn't be you.

903
00:48:22,987 --> 00:48:25,406
You know, it's not like 
I haven't heard that before.

904
00:48:25,448 --> 00:48:28,784
I guess I just, uh, never
really listened, that's all.

905
00:48:30,995 --> 00:48:33,956
Ain't nobody ever put
it that sweet, I guess.

906
00:48:51,182 --> 00:48:53,100
You know what,
Miss Della Bea Antwine?

907
00:48:53,142 --> 00:48:55,269
You really are a country girl.
You know that?

908
00:48:55,352 --> 00:48:57,313
Yes.
How'd you know?

909
00:48:57,396 --> 00:48:59,440
I could tell by
the way you ordered.

910
00:48:59,523 --> 00:49:01,692
"Let me get molasses
with my cornbread."

911
00:49:02,943 --> 00:49:04,612
Were you raised on a farm?

912
00:49:04,695 --> 00:49:07,531
My mother did a little 
sharecropping in Florida.

913
00:49:07,615 --> 00:49:09,074
Is she still there?

914
00:49:09,158 --> 00:49:11,994
God bless her heart, she passed 
away when I went to school.

915
00:49:12,077 --> 00:49:13,579
Ray, I'm sorry.

916
00:49:14,038 --> 00:49:15,748
She never was real healthy.

917
00:49:15,831 --> 00:49:18,375
She just worked herself 
to death, poor thing.

918
00:49:18,501 --> 00:49:21,253
That's why she didn't want me 
carrying around no tin cup.

919
00:49:21,337 --> 00:49:23,047
The kids I went to school with,

920
00:49:23,130 --> 00:49:25,800
they were doing basket-weavin'
and wickerwork.

921
00:49:26,675 --> 00:49:28,969
But not you. Because of your gift.

922
00:49:29,094 --> 00:49:30,721
Because of my ears.

923
00:49:31,013 --> 00:49:32,932
See, I can mimic
damn near anybody,

924
00:49:33,015 --> 00:49:35,684
and I ... I ... I ... I make
a pretty decent living at it.

925
00:49:35,768 --> 00:49:37,812
It's just, if I
change my style up ...

926
00:49:37,895 --> 00:49:39,438
and people really don't dig it,

927
00:49:39,522 --> 00:49:41,774
I mean, what am I
left with, you know?

928
00:49:42,024 --> 00:49:44,360
I mean, when you're blind,
Miss Antwine,

929
00:49:44,527 --> 00:49:46,612
you ain't got that many choices.

930
00:49:47,863 --> 00:49:50,324
Seem to me like you got all
the choices in the world.

931
00:49:51,534 --> 00:49:53,327
God gave you the gift to sound ...

932
00:49:53,369 --> 00:49:55,663
like anybody you please,
even yourself.

933
00:49:57,414 --> 00:49:59,625
We're here. This is where I live.

934
00:50:00,751 --> 00:50:02,586
Well, you think
the preacher'd let me in?

935
00:50:02,670 --> 00:50:05,005
I mean, uh, I'm a sinner,
but I need a little prayer.

936
00:50:05,047 --> 00:50:07,550
His wife don't like
me having male company.

937
00:50:07,675 --> 00:50:10,803
Well, tell him there's
a soul out here that needs savin'.

938
00:50:11,554 --> 00:50:14,974
You know what, Miss Antwine,
you really got me thinkin'.

939
00:50:16,809 --> 00:50:18,269
About what?

940
00:50:18,394 --> 00:50:21,689
About my life. About my music.

941
00:50:23,816 --> 00:50:25,317
About everything.

942
00:50:27,570 --> 00:50:31,031
Ray, don't ... don't you think
we're movin' a little fast?

943
00:50:32,992 --> 00:50:34,743
Listen, I'm ... I'm gonna
go to New York ...

944
00:50:34,827 --> 00:50:37,329
for a couple of weeks,
and when I get back,

945
00:50:37,746 --> 00:50:40,207
you can take it as
slow as you want.

946
00:50:42,877 --> 00:50:44,712
All right, Mr. Charles.

947
00:50:46,088 --> 00:50:47,840
All right, Miss Antwine.

948
00:50:48,257 --> 00:50:49,884
I'll see you in a couple of weeks.

949
00:50:49,925 --> 00:50:51,969
Well, hold on, now.
Let me call you a cab.

950
00:50:52,052 --> 00:50:53,721
I got it. Three blocks up,

951
00:50:53,804 --> 00:50:56,515
left for two, right for one.

952
00:50:56,599 --> 00:50:58,309
Fifteen giant steps,

953
00:50:58,392 --> 00:51:00,311
and I'm at the
Crystal White Hotel. Hello.

954
00:51:07,568 --> 00:51:10,154
"Mess Around" was
a positive step for us, Ray.

955
00:51:10,237 --> 00:51:11,363
We're making progress.

956
00:51:11,447 --> 00:51:13,574
Oh, come on, Ahmet.
Now, you've been nice to me.

957
00:51:13,657 --> 00:51:15,409
But I haven't given
you guys any hits.

958
00:51:15,493 --> 00:51:17,036
Atlantic Records
has been good to me,

959
00:51:17,119 --> 00:51:18,829
but if you want me to do
something special,

960
00:51:18,913 --> 00:51:20,247
I'm gonna need my own band.

961
00:51:20,748 --> 00:51:23,959
Oh, man. Taking a band out on 
the road costs a mint, Ray.

962
00:51:24,043 --> 00:51:27,087
I mean, even Joe Morris is struggling. 
His band's had a hit record.

963
00:51:27,171 --> 00:51:29,006
But, Ahmet, listen,
I'm not Joe Morris.

964
00:51:29,089 --> 00:51:31,342
Man, you told me if I think
pennies, I get pennies.

965
00:51:31,425 --> 00:51:33,302
I'm thinking dollars, man.

966
00:51:34,637 --> 00:51:37,473
Ruth Brown's got
a tour booked in Georgia.

967
00:51:38,599 --> 00:51:39,809
She needs a band.

968
00:51:39,892 --> 00:51:40,893
I ... I'll take it.

969
00:51:40,976 --> 00:51:43,729
I could write the charts
for her, I ... I could do backup,

970
00:51:43,813 --> 00:51:45,856
and also be an openin' act.

971
00:51:48,818 --> 00:51:50,152
Okay.

972
00:51:50,277 --> 00:51:52,530
But you're going to be
financially responsible.

973
00:51:52,613 --> 00:51:54,532
You're gonna have
to make it work, Ray.

974
00:51:54,615 --> 00:51:57,118
Yeah, yeah, I'm gonna make it
do what it do, baby.

975
00:51:57,201 --> 00:51:58,577
Yeah.

976
00:52:10,714 --> 00:52:11,715
Ray!

977
00:52:11,966 --> 00:52:14,385
Miss Antwine, it's been two weeks.

978
00:52:14,468 --> 00:52:16,178
It's been three.

979
00:52:21,851 --> 00:52:24,311
Now, where's the preacher at?
And the wife?

980
00:52:24,436 --> 00:52:26,522
They in Dallas till Monday.

981
00:52:26,605 --> 00:52:28,357
Well, hallelujah!

982
00:52:38,576 --> 00:52:39,994
Della Bea.

983
00:52:40,870 --> 00:52:42,663
Kind of like a honey bee, right?

984
00:52:46,584 --> 00:52:48,252
Can I call you Bea?

985
00:52:49,253 --> 00:52:51,547
Yeah, I'd like that.

986
00:52:54,425 --> 00:52:58,262
There's only been two cats that 
I ever really trusted in my life.

987
00:52:59,889 --> 00:53:03,017
There's Jeff Brown, he's going 
to be my tour manager,

988
00:53:03,893 --> 00:53:06,187
Fathead Newman, my tenor man ...

989
00:53:08,397 --> 00:53:09,857
and now you.

990
00:53:17,573 --> 00:53:18,949
But you gotta do me a favor.

991
00:53:19,033 --> 00:53:21,118
Bea, you gotta
always tell me the truth.

992
00:53:21,202 --> 00:53:23,329
Oh, yeah. 
Just like you did before.

993
00:53:24,205 --> 00:53:27,166
Don't feel sorry for me
just 'cause I'm blind.

994
00:53:28,292 --> 00:53:30,795
How could I pity
someone I admire?

995
00:53:35,800 --> 00:53:37,301
Can I play something for you?

996
00:53:37,384 --> 00:53:38,969
- Now?
- Yeah.

997
00:53:39,053 --> 00:53:40,179
No, Ray.

998
00:53:40,262 --> 00:53:42,181
Yeah, right now.
Right now. I'm gonna ...

999
00:53:42,264 --> 00:53:43,390
Ray!

1000
00:53:47,269 --> 00:53:49,146
It's right there.
You got it.

1001
00:53:49,271 --> 00:53:50,439
Okay.

1002
00:53:50,523 --> 00:53:51,732
Yeah, yeah, this will work.

1003
00:53:52,942 --> 00:53:55,236
Now you go ahead and play. 
I'm gonna close these drapes.

1004
00:53:55,319 --> 00:53:56,320
All right.

1005
00:53:56,403 --> 00:53:57,905
I don't want no
neighbors looking in.

1006
00:53:57,988 --> 00:53:59,406
♪ Well ♪

1007
00:53:59,949 --> 00:54:01,575
♪ I got a woman ♪

1008
00:54:02,576 --> 00:54:03,994
